        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity and Requested Wavelength Band:
The sensitivity requirement is driven by the aim to detect a disk of about 0.01 Jupiter masses around GQ Lup b. For T Tauri star dust disk spectra falling as wavelength to the -2.5 power or steeper, this is achieved most efficiently with ALMA using band 7 (although band 6 is competitive). For standard assumptions, this small mass corresponds to about 0.16 mJy. We request an rms of 0.032 mJy to obtain a solid 5 sigma detection at this level. This sensitivity
is also sufficient to reveal a hypothetical outer disk component of 5-10 mJy, as shown by our simulations (see proposal Figure 2). The line aspect of the proposal is secondary. The strengths of the 12CO and 13CO 3-2 lines are expected to be at least a few K from the GQ Lup A disk (if they are not confused by ambient cloud emission), so the expected rms of 1.0 K (2.8 mJy) per beam per 0.85 km/s velocity interval is sufficient.

Imaging requirements:
The 0.17 arcsec resolution is driven by the need to (1) cleanly resolve the companion from the primary at a separation of 0.7 arcsec, and (2) resolve structure within the 0.7 arcsec diameter disk around the primary. If the putative radial velocity companion clears a cavity, then this feature is readily detectable at the requested sensitivity down to about 5~AU radius through a null in the (deprojected) visibility function at about 1000 kilolambda.
Therefore we request baselines that reach to about 1 km in band 7.  To be sensitive to a possible outer disk with diameter approaching 400 AU, a maximum angular scale of 2.4 arcsec is needed. All of the structures easily fit within a single pointing. Dynamic range should not be an issue (especially with self-calibration).

Correlator setup:
We aim for the best continuum sensitivity and therefore request the maximum 7.5 GHz bandwidth. The basebands with the 12CO and 13CO 3-2 lines are set up with spectral resolution adequate (0.976 MHz = 0.85 km/s) for the expected linewidths of a few km/s from Keplerian rotation around the star. 

Calibration: No special calibrations are required.

Bandpass accuracy: Standard calibration is sufficient.

Scheduling/time constratints: None

Data rate: Within normal limits.

Special constraints on standard observing modes: None.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
